The paper discusses the fundamental limits of routing scalability in the Internet, which is a topic closely related to computer networks (cs.NI). The paper also discusses compact routing, which is a field of study in computer science that deals with designing algorithms for routing with smaller routing tables (cs.DS). The paper uses analytic arguments and simulations to support its findings, which are related to information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper discusses the need for a fundamental re-examination of assumptions behind routing models and abstractions, which is related to systems and control (cs.SI).
